{"showCoverPage":false,"bookCover":{"coverDescription":"<p style=\"text-align:center\"></p>"},"chapters":[{"params":{"content":[{"content":{"params":{"text":"<p> </p>\n\n<p><span style=\"font-size:1.5em\">SSH</span></p>\n\n<p>SSH allows us to remotely connect to another computer over a network. By connecting to the Pi via SSH, we can connect wirelessly and access the PI's files on another computer which will be neccessary when creating our own machine learning model. For more information on SSH, see <a href=\"https://youtu.be/v45p_kJV9i4\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>.</p>\n\n<p><span style=\"font-size:1.5em\">Enabling SSH</span></p>\n\n<p>To connect the the Pi through SSH, it has to be enable. Connect to the Pi through Serial ports and once you've logged in through the terminal, type the command:</p>\n\n<pre><code>sudo raspi-config</code></pre>\n\n<p>This will launch the rasperry pi configuration tool. Under <code>3 Interface Options</code>, choose <code>12 SSH</code> to enable ssh and select <code>Yes</code>. You can close the configuration program and reboot now with <code>shutdown -r now</code>.</p>\n\n<p>When SSH is enabled, anyone on your network can connect to your computer if they know the user and password, so be sure to keep your password secret.</p>\n\n<p> </p>\n"},"library":"H5P.AdvancedText 1.1","metadata":{"contentType":"Text","license":"U","title":"Untitled Text","authors":[],"changes":[]},"subContentId":"9ed3ba30-2ff5-409e-aa6d-285dbcc3620d"},"useSeparator":"auto"},{"content":{"params":{"imageSlides":[{"params":{"image":{"params":{"decorative":false,"contentName":"Image","file":{"path":"images/file-6lgJyFgY.png","mime":"image/png","copyright":{"license":"U"},"width":819,"height":509},"alt":"config menu"},"library":"H5P.Image 1.1","subContentId":"335013f2-1026-462a-a3cc-1c4df5db6451","metadata":{"contentType":"Image","license":"U","title":"Untitled Image","authors":[],"changes":[]}}},"library":"H5P.ImageSlide 1.1","subContentId":"dbcac481-068b-4c2d-a73e-848df3183366","metadata":{"contentType":"Image Slide","license":"U","title":"Config menu","authors":[],"changes":[],"extraTitle":"Config menu"}},{"params":{"image":{"params":{"decorative":false,"contentName":"Image","file":{"path":"images/file-pbDZpaAU.png","mime":"image/png","copyright":{"license":"U"},"width":797,"height":509},"alt":"Interface menu"},"library":"H5P.Image 1.1","subContentId":"eafb5d1c-f6c0-47ee-8cc3-f52e48d1e36f","metadata":{"contentType":"Image","license":"U","title":"Untitled Image","authors":[],"changes":[]}}},"library":"H5P.ImageSlide 1.1","subContentId":"09253572-065e-4265-bbfa-5582fe32fcac","metadata":{"contentType":"Image Slide","license":"U","title":"interface menu","authors":[],"changes":[],"extraTitle":"interface menu"}},{"params":{"image":{"params":{"decorative":false,"contentName":"Image","file":{"path":"images/file-CDYrMXgH.png","mime":"image/png","copyright":{"license":"U"},"width":813,"height":517},"alt":"enable ssh?"},"library":"H5P.Image 1.1","subContentId":"ee3d0aec-d8d7-4ee7-9c2c-fd78b9417290","metadata":{"contentType":"Image","license":"U","title":"Untitled Image","authors":[],"changes":[]}}},"library":"H5P.ImageSlide 1.1","subContentId":"de0c4b1e-43a9-41c3-a784-3fc007792b87","metadata":{"contentType":"Image Slide","license":"U","title":"Enable SSH?","authors":[],"changes":[],"extraTitle":"Enable SSH?"}}],"aspectRatioMode":"auto","aspectRatio":{"aspectWidth":4,"aspectHeight":3},"a11y":{"nextSlide":"Next Image","prevSlide":"Previous Image","gotoSlide":"Go to image %slide"}},"library":"H5P.ImageSlider 1.1","metadata":{"contentType":"Image Slider","license":"U","title":"enabling SSH","authors":[],"changes":[],"extraTitle":"enabling SSH"},"subContentId":"9fafb69c-e756-4189-a73a-5ea25c62561a"},"useSeparator":"auto"},{"content":{"params":{"intro":"<p>What does the warning say when asked if you want to enable SSH?</p>\n","summaries":[{"subContentId":"21f4f0b6-aa7e-4029-a20d-ecf6c9ab4318","summary":["<p>Default and weak passwords are a security risk when SSH is enabled! &nbsp;</p>\n","<p>Make sure the network is secure before enabling SSH.</p>\n","<p>Enabling SSH could make this device vulnerable to attacks, are you sure you want to continue?</p>\n"],"tip":""}],"overallFeedback":[{"from":0,"to":100}],"solvedLabel":"Progress:","scoreLabel":"Wrong answers:","resultLabel":"Your result","labelCorrect":"Correct.","labelIncorrect":"Incorrect! Please try again.","alternativeIncorrectLabel":"Incorrect","labelCorrectAnswers":"Correct answers.","tipButtonLabel":"Show tip","scoreBarLabel":"You got :num out of :total points","progressText":"Progress :num of :total"},"library":"H5P.Summary 1.10","metadata":{"contentType":"Summary","license":"U","title":"Untitled Summary","authors":[],"changes":[],"extraTitle":"Untitled Summary"},"subContentId":"ecc5f83e-3995-4aba-ac33-37b9e7447b15"},"useSeparator":"auto"}]},"library":"H5P.Column 1.15","subContentId":"f44fe1e0-3c32-4afd-9f5b-70f5381221a9","metadata":{"contentType":"Column","license":"U","title":"Enabling SSH","authors":[],"changes":[],"extraTitle":"Enabling SSH"}},{"params":{"content":[{"content":{"params":{"text":"<p> </p>\n\n<p><span style=\"font-size:1.5em\">Network Address</span></p>\n\n<p>If you have connected the Pi to the network, it has been given an address. You can find this address by typing</p>\n\n<pre><code>hostname -I\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Into the terminal.</p>\n\n<p>It will return an IPv4 address (it will look like 4 numbers separated by dots, ie 192.168.3.23) and a IPv6 address (it will look something like 0ab0:0102:5e5e:2b00:5ac3:56af). We can use the IPv4 address to connect to the Pi via SFTP.</p>\n\n<p> </p>\n"},"library":"H5P.AdvancedText 1.1","metadata":{"contentType":"Text","license":"U","title":"Untitled Text","authors":[],"changes":[]},"subContentId":"6b4da9c7-9583-43eb-91b7-47c9d051cff8"},"useSeparator":"auto"},{"content":{"params":{"decorative":false,"contentName":"Image","file":{"path":"images/file-OtrZm9pd.png","mime":"image/png","copyright":{"license":"U"},"width":816,"height":84},"alt":"Hostname -I and output in terminal"},"library":"H5P.Image 1.1","metadata":{"contentType":"Image","license":"U","title":"Untitled Image","authors":[],"changes":[]},"subContentId":"68c2c195-82fa-43bb-87fc-3e01e8eb728e"},"useSeparator":"auto"},{"content":{"params":{"text":"<p> </p>\n\n<p><span style=\"font-size:1.5em\">Connecting via SSH</span></p>\n\n<p>Opening PuTTY, make sure Connection type is set to SSH, type in the IP address of the Pi we just found and set the port to 22. Click 'Open' and a new terminal window should open and a login prompt should appear like before.</p>\n"},"library":"H5P.AdvancedText 1.1","metadata":{"contentType":"Text","license":"U","title":"Untitled Text","authors":[],"changes":[]},"subContentId":"85efa971-346f-440d-afea-8988ae0cfb93"},"useSeparator":"auto"},{"content":{"params":{"decorative":false,"contentName":"Image","file":{"path":"images/file-FLbFreRv.png","mime":"image/png","copyright":{"license":"U"},"width":580,"height":529},"alt":"Putty connection screen"},"library":"H5P.Image 1.1","metadata":{"contentType":"Image","license":"U","title":"Untitled Image","authors":[],"changes":[]},"subContentId":"09d4ea9f-402c-4ce4-b4fb-7132fb21376a"},"useSeparator":"auto"},{"content":{"params":{"media":{"disableImageZooming":false},"text":"Fill in the missing words","overallFeedback":[{"from":0,"to":100}],"showSolutions":"Show solution","tryAgain":"Retry","checkAnswer":"Check","submitAnswer":"Submit","notFilledOut":"Please fill in all blanks to view solution","answerIsCorrect":"&#039;:ans&#039; is correct","answerIsWrong":"&#039;:ans&#039; is wrong","answeredCorrectly":"Answered correctly","answeredIncorrectly":"Answered incorrectly","solutionLabel":"Correct answer:","inputLabel":"Blank input @num of @total","inputHasTipLabel":"Tip available","tipLabel":"Tip","behaviour":{"enableRetry":true,"enableSolutionsButton":true,"enableCheckButton":true,"autoCheck":false,"caseSensitive":true,"showSolutionsRequiresInput":true,"separateLines":false,"confirmCheckDialog":false,"confirmRetryDialog":false,"acceptSpellingErrors":false},"scoreBarLabel":"You got :num out of :total points","a11yCheck":"Check the answers. The responses will be marked as correct, incorrect, or unanswered.","a11yShowSolution":"Show the solution. The task will be marked with its correct solution.","a11yRetry":"Retry the task. Reset all responses and start the task over again.","a11yCheckingModeHeader":"Checking mode","confirmCheck":{"header":"Finish ?","body":"Are you sure you wish to finish ?","cancelLabel":"Cancel","confirmLabel":"Finish"},"confirmRetry":{"header":"Retry ?","body":"Are you sure you wish to retry ?","cancelLabel":"Cancel","confirmLabel":"Confirm"},"questions":["<p>When you open a new SSH connection to the Pi, the first thing printed on the terminal is *login as: *.</p>\n"]},"library":"H5P.Blanks 1.14","metadata":{"contentType":"Fill in the Blanks","license":"U","title":"login prompt","authors":[],"changes":[],"extraTitle":"login prompt"},"subContentId":"2427441b-be38-4b88-969d-2ea08c70b246"},"useSeparator":"auto"}]},"library":"H5P.Column 1.15","subContentId":"cda37f01-6eda-4245-a7f7-5d1d4f46a74a","metadata":{"contentType":"Column","license":"U","title":"Connecting through SSH","authors":[],"changes":[],"extraTitle":"Connecting through SSH"}},{"params":{"content":[{"content":{"params":{"text":"<p> </p>\n\n<p><span style=\"font-size:1.5em\">Raspberry Pi Terminal</span></p>\n\n<p>The only way to work in Raspabarian Lite is via the terminal. To log into a fresh Pi, use username pi and password raspberry.</p>\n"},"library":"H5P.AdvancedText 1.1","metadata":{"contentType":"Text","license":"U","title":"Untitled Text","authors":[],"changes":[]},"subContentId":"e817b454-9176-49c9-a0f0-2c63bb7e9457"},"useSeparator":"auto"},{"content":{"params":{"iconType":"icon","icon":"plus","color":"#4bc53c","hotspots":[{"position":{"x":86.86978599927457,"y":29.26861695848444},"alwaysFullscreen":false,"content":[{"params":{"text":"<p>This information will appear every time you log into your Pi, feel free to ignore it.</p>\n"},"library":"H5P.Text 1.1","metadata":{"contentType":"Text","license":"U","title":"Untitled Text","authors":[],"changes":[]},"subContentId":"e0605d2e-08d8-4190-bf4a-82c261d0ab54"}]},{"position":{"x":25.38991657598839,"y":48.17162355507706},"alwaysFullscreen":false,"content":[{"params":{"text":"<p>The command prompt will appear once you've logged in and it is where you can run commands in the terminal. The prompt consists of the username (in your case it will be pi) and the hostname (in the picture this is raspberrypi) which are both in green and separated by an @. In the blue is the current directory, and as you move through the pi it will change to show the path to the directory you're currently in.</p>\n"},"library":"H5P.Text 1.1","metadata":{"contentType":"Text","license":"U","title":"Untitled Text","authors":[],"changes":[]},"subContentId":"b9ca8a14-8b65-4ea7-ae8b-5816588d4d52"}],"header":"Command Prompt"},{"position":{"x":72.39999999999999,"y":47.62509468146086},"alwaysFullscreen":false,"content":[{"params":{"text":"<p>This is where you can type in your commands, we will explain some of the commands you'll be using in the next section.</p>\n"},"library":"H5P.Text 1.1","metadata":{"contentType":"Text","license":"U","title":"Untitled Text","authors":[],"changes":[]},"subContentId":"c278dbb2-f96d-4135-bf69-4afa6af8888d"}],"header":"Command Line"}],"hotspotNumberLabel":"Hotspot #num","closeButtonLabel":"Close","image":{"path":"images/image-28YCpkNx.png","mime":"image/png","copyright":{"license":"U"},"width":793,"height":469}},"library":"H5P.ImageHotspots 1.10","metadata":{"contentType":"Image Hotspots","license":"U","title":"Terminal screen","authors":[],"changes":[],"extraTitle":"Terminal screen"},"subContentId":"5d62cf2f-63d1-4255-9ba8-7fcc338fc5ea"},"useSeparator":"auto"},{"content":{"params":{"text":"<p><span style=\"font-size:1.5em\">Common Commands</span></p>\n\n<p>In order to navigate the terminal, there are a few commands that are important to know:</p>\n\n<p>- ls: this command lists the files and directories (folders) that are inside of the current directory.</p>\n\n<p>- cd {directorypath}: this command changes the directory you are in and enters the directory that you specify in the command.</p>\n\n<p>- nano {filename}: this command with create and open the specified file. The user can then read and edit the file in the terminal.</p>\n\n<p>To Learn how to navigate through the Pi's terminal, have a go at <a href=\"https://mqmlworkshop.h5p.com/content/1291695548015558809\" target=\"_blank\">this terminal activity.</a></p>\n\n<p><span style=\"font-size:1.5em\">Sudo</span></p>\n\n<p>Throughout this workshop you may notice the word sudo in a few of the commands you'll run. Sudo allows a user more priviledges than what they would usually have. For this workshop, you'll be using it to access the configuration menu and installing some tools to run the machine learning models. For more info, check out <a href=\"https://acloudguru.com/blog/engineering/linux-commands-for-beginners-sudo#:~:text=Sudo%2C%20the%20one%20command%20to,important%20commands%20in%20your%20arsenal.\" target=\"_blank\">this website</a></p>\n"},"library":"H5P.AdvancedText 1.1","metadata":{"contentType":"Text","license":"U","title":"Untitled Text","authors":[],"changes":[]},"subContentId":"f7ae1ba0-36e0-41b3-9d5c-8168a1925d4b"},"useSeparator":"auto"}]},"library":"H5P.Column 1.15","subContentId":"bd25888d-e1ca-4f35-832a-36eefc111df1","metadata":{"contentType":"Column","license":"U","title":"Terminal Basics","authors":[],"changes":[],"extraTitle":"Terminal Basics"}}],"behaviour":{"defaultTableOfContents":true,"progressIndicators":true,"progressAuto":true,"displaySummary":true,"baseColor":"#1768c4"},"read":"Read","displayTOC":"Display &#039;Table of contents&#039;","hideTOC":"Hide &#039;Table of contents&#039;","nextPage":"Next page",